## road
- [x] Put a single triangle on screen using barycentric rasterization. No camera, no matrices — just three 2D points.
- [ ] Add the MVP pipeline and draw a spinning cube.
- [ ] Add the Z-buffer. Draw two intersecting triangles and verify correct occlusion.
- [ ] Add perspective-correct interpolation. Test it explicitly — draw a checkered quad receding into the distance; if the checks distort, you got it wrong. This is the step where half of self-taught graphics people have a subtle bug they never notice.
- [ ] Load an OBJ file and texture it. Implement nearest-neighbor, then bilinear, then mipmaps + trilinear. Spend time looking at the artifacts at each stage. Make a scene that deliberately induces texture aliasing.
- [ ] Homogeneous clipping (against the near plane especially). Skipping this is the #2 source of mystery bugs.
- [ ] Shadow mapping, then IBL. By now you're essentially writing shaders in C++ functions.
- [ ] One anti-aliasing technique — MSAA in software is educational because you have to think about sample positions and coverage explicitly.

